cted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs researchers have begun to adapt to the continuing presence of COVID-19, they have also begun to reflect more deeply on fundamental research issues and assumptions. Researchers around the world have responded in diverse, thoughtful and creative ways – from adapting data collection methods to fostering researcher and community resilience, while also attending to often urgent needs for care. This book, part of a series of three Rapid Responses, connects themes of care and resilience, addressing their common concern with wellbeing. It has three parts: addressing researchers’ wellbeing, considering participants’ wellbeing, and exploring care and resilience as a shared and mutually entangled concern. The other two books focus on Response and Reassessment, and Creativity and Ethics. Together they help academic, applied and practitioner-researchers worldwide adapt to the new challenges COVID-19 brings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aOVID-19 (Disease)xResearch. 0aSocial sciencesxResearch. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Methodology.2bisacsh1 aAdams, Eseoghene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdcock, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdjei, Stephen Baffour, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAkaba, Godwin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlheiwidi, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnaduaka, Uchechi Shirley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoynton, Petra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCramer, Emma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDay, Laurie,